[13] Prague: measles on the rise
Date: Tue 9 Apr 2019, 2:07 PM
Source: Prague.TV [abridged, edited]
https://protect2.fireeye.com/url?k=9d5c1ebe-c17912dd-9d5ee78b-0cc47aa88e08-2115eb5d0f63fdcd&u=https://prague.tv/en/s72/Directory/c202-Beauty-Health-Wellness/n17471-Measles-on-the-rise-in-Prague


Some 139 cases of measles have been registered in Prague since the beginning of the year [2019], which is an increase over last year [2018], which saw 103 cases by this time. Since the beginning of the measles outbreak at the start of 2018, there have been 242 confirmed cases in Prague. Anti-epidemic measures were applied against 2037 people and 902 faced quarantine or medical supervision.

According to Prague hygienists, people who have been vaccinated with only one dose of the vaccine should have their immunity tested via a blood sample. About one-third of people tested lack sufficient antibodies. This mainly concerns people born from 1967 to the first half of the 1970s, according to the Prague Hygiene Station.

Furthermore, hygienists recommend a test for antibodies in persons whose loved ones have reduced immunity. "For example, if the person is undergoing cancer treatment. People with immunodeficiency are more prone to all infectious diseases, including measles. Therefore, the environment of the oncological patient should be protected, and the patient cannot usually be vaccinated," Prague Hygiene Station spokesman Zbynek Boublik said.

New parents should also be tested for immunity. Small children are vaccinated in the Czech Republic only from the 13th month of age, while measles can have a serious effect in newborns and very young children. If the test shows a low level of antibodies in the parents, it is possible to vaccinate them to protect the children.

If a general practitioner issues an antibody test application, the insurance company pays for the examination. Otherwise, the test must be paid for by the candidate himself, but are only around CZK 350 [approx. 15 USD], depending on the lab.

The disease had been considered under control in the developed world but has
had a resurgence due to a drop in vaccination rates.

[Byline: Raymond Johnston]

